## **2. C (Carbon) vs Si (Silicon)**

**Group 14 – Valence Electrons: 4**

| Aspect            | **Carbon (C)**                | **Silicon (Si)**                      | **Reason for Differences**                                                  |
| ----------------- | ----------------------------- | ------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Orbital Number    | 2 energy levels (1s² 2s² 2p²) | 3 energy levels (1s² 2s² 2p⁶ 3s² 3p²) | Si has an additional shell → more shielding and less effective nuclear pull |
| Common Oxidation  | +4, +2                        | +4, +2                                | Similar, but Si⁺⁴ is more stable due to lower electronegativity             |
| Electronegativity | 2.55                          | 1.90                                  | C forms stronger covalent bonds; Si less so due to its larger size          |

---

## **3. N (Nitrogen) vs P (Phosphorus)**

**Group 15 – Valence Electrons: 5**

| Aspect            | **Nitrogen (N)**              | **Phosphorus (P)**           | **Reason for Differences**                                                   |
| ----------------- | ----------------------------- | ---------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Orbital Number    | 2 energy levels (1s² 2s² 2p³) | 3 energy levels (1s² to 3p³) | P has more shielding → lower ionization energy                               |
| Common Oxidation  | -3, +3, +5                    | -3, +3, +5                   | Both show same states, but P can expand octet (3d orbitals) → more stable +5 |
| Electronegativity | 3.04                          | 2.19                         | N attracts electrons more strongly due to smaller size and no d-orbitals     |

---

## **4. O (Oxygen) vs S (Sulfur)**

**Group 16 – Valence Electrons: 6**

| Aspect            | **Oxygen (O)**                | **Sulfur (S)**              | **Reason for Differences**                                                            |
| ----------------- | ----------------------------- | --------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Orbital Number    | 2 energy levels (1s² 2s² 2p⁴) | 3 energy levels (up to 3p⁴) | Extra shell in S → more shielding → weaker nuclear attraction                         |
| Common Oxidation  | -2                            | -2, +4, +6                  | S has access to empty 3d orbitals → can expand octet and form +4, +6 oxidation states |
| Electronegativity | 3.44                          | 2.58                        | O is the 2nd most electronegative element; strongly attracts electrons                |

